    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "17a33c37391af2ac",
      "text": "Comment sections on blogs are meant to extend a discussion on a post, and the participants are assumed to understand the larger conversation with which the post engages. Drive-by comments are a perversion of the medium which treat comments sections as a publishing platform or general forum, only loosely related to the post and the community with which it engages. [http://www.philosophyetc.net/2008/08/drive-by-commenting.html html]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f435062a6d7bbffc",
      "text": "Drive-by commenters often arrive from social media links -- Facebook, Twitter, Hacker News, Slashdot -- and leave comments primarily because they know the page is getting many views. In many cases they are posting the same idea, loosely related to the topic, on many blogs. A post on new research on women in STEM fields will spur reactions questioning the very existence of sexism, or claim media conspiracy on the issue."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "925d90982b7edd8d",
      "text": "Drive-by commenters often misunderstand blogging as article writing, and do not follow links to see what larger conversation the post belongs to. As such, they often claim victory when they identify supposed gaps in a posts' explanation of an issue, failing to realize that posts are meant to extend arguments, not present them in total. (And again, they fail to follow the links which often answer such questions). "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f380030f5c5e5093",
      "text": "Drive-by commenting used to be a rare phenomenon, the activity of someone who found your blog through Google, or ocassionally Slashdot. As people have moved from RSS readers to social media feeds the problem has become particularly intense, leading to many bloggers shutting comments, and some to leave blogging entirely."
    },
